04842nam a22006975i 9783110986938DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20242024gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2023950721  a97831109869387 a10.1515/97831109869382doi  a(DE-B1597)633725  a(OCoLC)1419788676  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aHIS0440002bisacsh02aA Mirror of the Jewish Religion: A Critical Edition and Translation of Christian Petter Löwe's "Speculum Religionis Judaicæ" (1732) /ced. by Jonathan Adams. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (XII, 333 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligious Minorities in the North : History, Politics, and Culture ,x2627-440X ;v600tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction -- tEdition -- tAppendices -- tAppendix 1: King Frederik I's privilege and other dedications -- tAppendix 2: Hebrew, Aramaic, and Yiddish words, terms, and phrases found in Speculum Religionis Judaicæ -- tAppendix 3: Prospectus (30 August 1731) -- tAppendix 4: Extra material in Speculum Religionis Judaicæ (Stockholm: Frantz Philip Paulssen, 1735) -- tAppendix 5: Excerpts from Christophorus Bezelius' Die Herrlichkeit des Christenthums (Stockholm: Heinrich Käyser, 1684) -- tAppendix 6: Christian Gottlieb Seeligmann, Jüdischer Ceremonien (1725) -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aIn 1732, Christian Petter Löwe, a Jewish convert to Lutheranism, published his Speculum Religionis Judaicæ (Mirror of the Jewish Religion), a description of the Jewish religion and ceremonies as practised at the time. Over 50 years before Jews were permitted to settle in Sweden in 1782, the genre of Christian ethnographical writing about Jews and Jewish rituals had arrived in Sweden from Germany. In this volume, Jonathan Adams (University of Gothenburg) introduces the background to Löwe's "mirror" by looking at both the earlier history of Jews in Sweden and the phenomenon of ethnographical writing about Jews. The text of Speculum is presented in its original Swedish with a translation into English facing on the opposite pages. This edition includes notes explaining technical terms, identifying people and places, and translating Hebrew words and phrases. The volume also includes two works published in Sweden prior to Speculum: Bezelius' Die Herrlichkeit des Christenthums (The Glory of Christianity [excerpts], 1684) and Seeligmann's Jüdischer Ceremonien (On Jewish Ceremonies, 1725). The volume should be of interest to students and researchers of Jewish and Scandinavian history as well as the history of Jewish-Christian relations.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Vetenskapsrådet / The Swedish Research Council  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aChristian Petter Löwe. 4aEdition. 4aFrühe Neuzeit. 4aJudentum. 4aschwedische Literatur. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Scandinavia.2bisacsh  aChristian Petter Löwe.  aJudaism.  aSwedish text.  aearly modern period.  aedition.1 aAdams, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt2 aVetenskapsrådet / The Swedish Research Councilefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG0 cprintz978311099841240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110986938zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110986938zOpen Access70423Coveruh